title: Speech Pen: New Pen Input Interface Capable of Utilizing Speech Recognition for Digital Writing
title_en: Speech Pen: New Pen Input Interface Capable of Utilizing Speech Recognition for Digital Writing
abstract: 本研究は講義やプレゼンテーションでのデジタル書き込みを支援するために、音声認識とペン入力の統合を提案している。提案するシステムは音声認識の多仮説出力をペン入力と統合してあいまい性を低減し、予測提示と共有機能で講師の筆記負担軽減と聴衆のノート取得支援を目指している。
abstract_en: This paper proposes integrating speech recognition with pen input to support digital writing in lectures and presentations. The proposed system integrates multiple speech-recognition hypotheses with pen input to reduce ambiguity and uses prediction and sharing features to reduce presenter writing load and assist audience note-taking.
positioning_summary: 本研究はデジタル筆記における音声認識と手書き入力の統合を位置づけており、講義やプレゼンテーションという文脈での筆記負担と聴衆のノート取得の困難さという課題に対処している。位置づけとして本研究はタブレットPCや電子ホワイトボード上での講師と聴衆を対象に、音声と手書きのマルチモーダル統合が重要であると示している。
positioning_summary_en: This research positions the integration of speech recognition and handwriting input within digital writing, addressing presenter writing load and audience note-taking difficulties in lectures and presentations. The positioning emphasizes that multimodal integration of speech and pen input is important for tablet PCs and electronic whiteboards used by presenters and audiences.
purpose_summary: 本研究の目的は講師が話しながら書く通常の環境で発生する手書き負担と聴衆のノート取りのギャップを埋めることである。目的として本研究は講義やプレゼンの講師と聴衆を対象にして、音声認識出力と筆記入力の統合により誤認識やあいまい性を低減することを目指している。
purpose_summary_en: The purpose of this research is to bridge the gap between presenter handwriting burden and audience note-taking difficulties in normal lecture settings. The purpose targets lecturers and audiences in lectures and presentations, aiming to reduce recognition errors and ambiguity by integrating speech recognition outputs with pen input.
method_summary: 本研究は音声認識のN-bestやコンフュージョンネットワークを用いて複数仮説を生成し、手書き認識と並列処理して次の筆記内容を予測表示するマルチモーダル入力システムを実装した。実装として本システムはクライアント／サーバ構成やタブレットPCプラットフォーム上で音声認識と筆記認識を統合し、講師が予測を受け入れて貼り付けるか無視できる操作と認識結果の共有機能を備えている。
method_summary_en: This research implements a multimodal input system that generates multiple speech-recognition hypotheses using N-best lists and confusion networks and processes them in parallel with handwriting recognition to predict and display upcoming writing. The implementation uses a client/server architecture and a tablet PC platform to integrate speech and pen recognition, providing controls for presenters to accept predicted text and a sharing function to distribute recognition results.
evaluation_summary: 本研究はワークショップや予備的なユーザ実験で評価を行い、評価方法としてワークショップ事例や操作時間の計測および指標 S = Nsup / Nall を用いた定量的検討を含んでいる。評価結果として本研究は予備的に本システムの有効性が示されたことを報告し、コンフュージョンネットワークの有用性や実験で観察された操作時間（例: 0:22 や 0:41 など）に基づく示唆が得られた。
evaluation_summary_en: The study evaluated the system in workshops and preliminary user experiments, using case observations, measured operation times, and a quantitative metric S = Nsup / Nall. The observed results indicate that the system showed preliminary effectiveness, suggesting the usefulness of confusion networks and improvements supported by measured operation times (e.g., 0:22 and 0:41).

Title: Speech Pen: New Pen Input Interface Capable of Utilizing Speech Recognition for Digital Writing
Authors: Kazutaka Kurihara, Takeo Igarashi, Masataka Goto, Jun Ogata
Year: 2005
Abstract: This paper proposes integrating speech recognition with pen input to support digital writing in lectures and presentations. The proposed system integrates multiple speech-recognition hypotheses with pen input to reduce ambiguity and uses prediction and sharing features to reduce presenter writing load and assist audience note-taking.
Positioning Summary: This research positions the integration of speech recognition and handwriting input within digital writing, addressing presenter writing load and audience note-taking difficulties in lectures and presentations. The positioning emphasizes that multimodal integration of speech and pen input is important for tablet PCs and electronic whiteboards used by presenters and audiences.
Purpose Summary: The purpose of this research is to bridge the gap between presenter handwriting burden and audience note-taking difficulties in normal lecture settings. The purpose targets lecturers and audiences in lectures and presentations, aiming to reduce recognition errors and ambiguity by integrating speech recognition outputs with pen input.
Method Summary: This research implements a multimodal input system that generates multiple speech-recognition hypotheses using N-best lists and confusion networks and processes them in parallel with handwriting recognition to predict and display upcoming writing. The implementation uses a client/server architecture and a tablet PC platform to integrate speech and pen recognition, providing controls for presenters to accept predicted text and a sharing function to distribute recognition results.
Evaluation Summary: The study evaluated the system in workshops and preliminary user experiments, using case observations, measured operation times, and a quantitative metric S = Nsup / Nall. The observed results indicate that the system showed preliminary effectiveness, suggesting the usefulness of confusion networks and improvements supported by measured operation times (e.g., 0:22 and 0:41).
